        {
            "texttype":"Online",
            "textpurpose":"Gallery Label",
            "textentryhtml":"After its founding in 1804, the Sokoto Caliphate adopted the riga as its official ceremonial dress. Modeled after a gown of the same name worn by Hausa communities, conquered during the caliphate’s expansion, the cotton robe represents the unity and authority of the powerful Islamic caliphate. Artisans and workers from all levels of society supported the production of these robes. Enslaved laborers grew and processed the raw cotton. Free and enslaved men, some captured from Yorùbá kingdoms to the south, wove the cotton thread into strips on a double heddle loom. Tailors, often living in cities, sewed the cotton strips into garments that were embroidered by itinerant Muslim scholars. The white of this riga and its fine embroidery is associated with sanctity and purity in Islam. Color appears only on the interior, in the magenta of the imported <i>alharini </i>silk lining the bottom edge.\n",
            "remarks":"AFR_31_CLA.pdf - Day 1 installation"
        }
    ],
